{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01LmVe9evT7RTU9Tyt8yTDZH","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Wire web UI \"Trigger Orchestrator\" button to actual orchestrator\n     2→\n     3→## Context\n     4→\n     5→The web dashboard has a \"Trigger Orchestrator\" button on each project card (in `projects.html`). The frontend already sends a POST to `/api/projects/{label}/trigger` with the project label and dir. However, the backend handler `handleAPITriggerOrchestrator` in `internal/adapters/web/handler.go` is a stub that just returns 202 without doing anything.\n     6→\n     7→The gRPC server already has orchestration wired up via `SetOrchestrateFunc`. The web handler needs the same capability.\n     8→\n     9→## Implementation\n    10→\n    11→### 1. Add an orchestrate function field to the web Handler (`internal/adapters/web/handler.go`)\n    12→\n    13→Add a new field to the `Handler` struct:\n    14→\n    15→```go\n    16→orchestrateFn func(ctx context.Context, projectDir string) (int, error)\n    17→```\n    18→\n    19→Add a `HandlerOption` for it:\n    20→\n    21→```go\n    22→func WithOrchestrateFunc(fn func(ctx context.Context, projectDir string) (int, error)) HandlerOption {\n    23→    return func(h *Handler) { h.orchestrateFn = fn }\n    24→}\n    25→```\n    26→\n    27→### 2. Update `handleAPITriggerOrchestrator` to call the orchestrator\n    28→\n    29→The handler receives a project **label** in the URL path (e.g. \"myproject\"). It needs to resolve that back to a project **directory** using the store. Here's what it should do:\n    30→\n    31→1. Get the label from `r.PathValue(\"name\")`\n    32→2. Call `h.store.ListProjects(r.Context())` and build `projectLabels(projects)` to get the label→dir mapping\n    33→3. Find the project dir that maps to the given label. If not found, return 404.\n    34→4. If `h.orchestrateFn` is nil, return 501 (Not Implemented) with a JSON error message.\n    35→5. Call `h.orchestrateFn(r.Context(), projectDir)`\n    36→6. On error, return 500 with the error message in JSON.\n    37→7. On success, return 200 with JSON `{\"status\": \"ok\", \"project\": label, \"dispatched\": N}` where N is the count returned by the orchestrate function.\n    38→\n    39→### 3. Update the frontend to send `dir` as a query parameter (`internal/adapters/web/templates/projects.html`)\n    40→\n    41→The JS `triggerOrchestrator` function already receives `dir` as a parameter but doesn't send it. Update the `fetch` call to include the dir as a query parameter:\n    42→\n    43→```js\n    44→fetch('/api/projects/' + encodeURIComponent(label) + '/trigger?dir=' + encodeURIComponent(dir), {method: 'POST'})\n    45→```\n    46→\n    47→Actually, looking more carefully, the better approach is to resolve label→dir server-side via the store (as described in step 2), so no frontend change is needed.\n    48→\n    49→### 4. Wire it up in the daemon (`cmd/cloched/main.go`)\n    50→\n    51→Where the web handler is created (around line 110), pass the orchestrate function:\n    52→\n    53→```go\n    54→webOpts := []web.HandlerOption{\n    55→    web.WithContainerLogger(runtime),\n    56→    web.WithLogStore(store),\n    57→    web.WithLogBroadcaster(broadcaster),\n    58→}\n    59→if orch != nil {\n    60→    webOpts = append(webOpts, web.WithOrchestrateFunc(func(ctx context.Context, projectDir string) (int, error) {\n    61→        return orch.Run(ctx, projectDir)\n    62→    }))\n    63→}\n    64→webHandler, err := web.NewHandler(store, store, webOpts...)\n    65→```\n    66→\n    67→### 5. Update the test (`internal/adapters/web/handler_test.go`)\n    68→\n    69→Update `TestAPITriggerOrchestrator` to test both cases:\n    70→\n    71→**Without orchestrator (nil):** POST should return 501 with an error message.\n    72→\n    73→**With orchestrator:**\n    74→- Create a handler with `WithOrchestrateFunc` that returns a known dispatched count\n    75→- POST with a label that matches a project in the store\n    76→- Assert 200 response with correct JSON including dispatched count\n    77→\n    78→Also test the case where the project label doesn't match any known project (should 404).\n    79→\n    80→### 6. Update button feedback in the frontend\n    81→\n    82→After a successful trigger, update the button text to show how many runs were dispatched. For example: \"Dispatched 2 runs\" or \"No tasks ready\" (if dispatched is 0). The JS function should read the response JSON:\n    83→\n    84→```js\n    85→r.json().then(function(data) {\n    86→    if (data.dispatched > 0) {\n    87→        btn.textContent = 'Dispatched ' + data.dispatched;\n    88→    } else {\n    89→        btn.textContent = 'No tasks ready';\n    90→    }\n    91→    // ... existing timeout reset logic\n    92→});\n    93→```\n    94→\n    95→## Files to modify\n    96→- `internal/adapters/web/handler.go` — Add field, option, update handler\n    97→- `internal/adapters/web/templates/projects.html` — Update JS response handling\n    98→- `internal/adapters/web/handler_test.go` — Update test\n    99→- `cmd/cloched/main.go` — Wire orchestrate func to web handler\n   100→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"83efa890-2574-44c5-a1f7-226ad3f671c0","uuid":"40f9b193-cca4-4310-918b-f7f75c1d3be1","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/.cloche/prompt.txt","content":"# Wire web UI \"Trigger Orchestrator\" button to actual orchestrator\n\n## Context\n\nThe web dashboard has a \"Trigger Orchestrator\" button on each project card (in `projects.html`). The frontend already sends a POST to `/api/projects/{label}/trigger` with the project label and dir. However, the backend handler `handleAPITriggerOrchestrator` in `internal/adapters/web/handler.go` is a stub that just returns 202 without doing anything.\n\nThe gRPC server already has orchestration wired up via `SetOrchestrateFunc`. The web handler needs the same capability.\n\n## Implementation\n\n### 1. Add an orchestrate function field to the web Handler (`internal/adapters/web/handler.go`)\n\nAdd a new field to the `Handler` struct:\n\n```go\norchestrateFn func(ctx context.Context, projectDir string) (int, error)\n```\n\nAdd a `HandlerOption` for it:\n\n```go\nfunc WithOrchestrateFunc(fn func(ctx context.Context, projectDir string) (int, error)) HandlerOption {\n    return func(h *Handler) { h.orchestrateFn = fn }\n}\n```\n\n### 2. Update `handleAPITriggerOrchestrator` to call the orchestrator\n\nThe handler receives a project **label** in the URL path (e.g. \"myproject\"). It needs to resolve that back to a project **directory** using the store. Here's what it should do:\n\n1. Get the label from `r.PathValue(\"name\")`\n2. Call `h.store.ListProjects(r.Context())` and build `projectLabels(projects)` to get the label→dir mapping\n3. Find the project dir that maps to the given label. If not found, return 404.\n4. If `h.orchestrateFn` is nil, return 501 (Not Implemented) with a JSON error message.\n5. Call `h.orchestrateFn(r.Context(), projectDir)`\n6. On error, return 500 with the error message in JSON.\n7. On success, return 200 with JSON `{\"status\": \"ok\", \"project\": label, \"dispatched\": N}` where N is the count returned by the orchestrate function.\n\n### 3. Update the frontend to send `dir` as a query parameter (`internal/adapters/web/templates/projects.html`)\n\nThe JS `triggerOrchestrator` function already receives `dir` as a parameter but doesn't send it. Update the `fetch` call to include the dir as a query parameter:\n\n```js\nfetch('/api/projects/' + encodeURIComponent(label) + '/trigger?dir=' + encodeURIComponent(dir), {method: 'POST'})\n```\n\nActually, looking more carefully, the better approach is to resolve label→dir server-side via the store (as described in step 2), so no frontend change is needed.\n\n### 4. Wire it up in the daemon (`cmd/cloched/main.go`)\n\nWhere the web handler is created (around line 110), pass the orchestrate function:\n\n```go\nwebOpts := []web.HandlerOption{\n    web.WithContainerLogger(runtime),\n    web.WithLogStore(store),\n    web.WithLogBroadcaster(broadcaster),\n}\nif orch != nil {\n    webOpts = append(webOpts, web.WithOrchestrateFunc(func(ctx context.Context, projectDir string) (int, error) {\n        return orch.Run(ctx, projectDir)\n    }))\n}\nwebHandler, err := web.NewHandler(store, store, webOpts...)\n```\n\n### 5. Update the test (`internal/adapters/web/handler_test.go`)\n\nUpdate `TestAPITriggerOrchestrator` to test both cases:\n\n**Without orchestrator (nil):** POST should return 501 with an error message.\n\n**With orchestrator:**\n- Create a handler with `WithOrchestrateFunc` that returns a known dispatched count\n- POST with a label that matches a project in the store\n- Assert 200 response with correct JSON including dispatched count\n\nAlso test the case where the project label doesn't match any known project (should 404).\n\n### 6. Update button feedback in the frontend\n\nAfter a successful trigger, update the button text to show how many runs were dispatched. For example: \"Dispatched 2 runs\" or \"No tasks ready\" (if dispatched is 0). The JS function should read the response JSON:\n\n```js\nr.json().then(function(data) {\n    if (data.dispatched > 0) {\n        btn.textContent = 'Dispatched ' + data.dispatched;\n    } else {\n        btn.textContent = 'No tasks ready';\n    }\n    // ... existing timeout reset logic\n});\n```\n\n## Files to modify\n- `internal/adapters/web/handler.go` — Add field, option, update handler\n- `internal/adapters/web/templates/projects.html` — Update JS response handling\n- `internal/adapters/web/handler_test.go` — Update test\n- `cmd/cloched/main.go` — Wire orchestrate func to web handler\n","numLines":100,"startLine":1,"totalLines":100}}}
